Carbon to Sea Initiative''s Ocean Alk-Align (received $11M USD in grants in 2023) indicates complex, multi-stakeholder project management and the need for strategic alignment across diverse research teams.","lat":44.6366,"lng":-63.5937,"contact_name":"Dr. Katja Fennel","contact_email":"Not publicly available (recommend faculty contact page)","contact_position":"Professor, Department of Oceanography and lead of Ocean Alk-Align consortium","contact_linkedin":"https://ca.linkedin.com/in/katja-fennel-5a639b5b (inferred from public info)","contact_bio":"Leading researcher in oceanography, particularly in ocean carbon cycling and alkalinity enhancement.","review_status":"Lead for Review","host_producer_notes":"Academic institution, but involved in significant, applied ocean research with commercialization potential. Leslie could advise on strategic partnerships and research translation. Dr. Fennel is a strong potential contact for initial outreach.","budget_tier":"small"},{"name":"Irving Shipbuilding Inc.","location":"Halifax, Nova Scotia","website":"https://www.irvingshipbuilding.com/","estimated_size":2000,"estimated_budget":"Billions (federal shipbuilding contract)","mission_focus":"Primary contractor for Canada''s National Shipbuilding Strategy, building and maintaining naval and Coast Guard vessels. Key player in ocean infrastructure and defense.","why_fit":"Irving Shipbuilding is engaged in a multi-billion dollar, multi-decade contract, presenting immense challenges in program management, supply chain complexity, and strategic alignment with government and numerous subcontractors. Leslie’s expertise in cross-sector complexity, strategic knots, and ensuring aligned outcomes would be highly beneficial in navigating such a large-scale, long-term national project.","keyword_category":"infra","signal_strength":"strong","leadership_signal_tier":"inferred","leadership_signal_evidence":"Ongoing steel cutting for River-class destroyers (March 2026) and continuous work on the