ssess leadership challenges. Recommend direct outreach to verify organizational context before pursuing.","lat":36.9741,"lng":-122.0308,"contact_name":"Dane Hardin","contact_email":"N/A (contact form on website)","contact_position":"Senior Marine Scientist, Principal","contact_linkedin":"N/A (not immediately found)","contact_bio":"Expert in quantitative marine studies and executive director of the Central Coast Long-term Environmental Assessment Network (CCLEAN).","review_status":"Lead for Review","host_producer_notes":"Consulting firm with strong technical expertise in environmental monitoring and regulatory compliance, particularly for energy and infrastructure projects. Worth investigating for strategic partnership opportunities.","budget_tier":"small"}]',13,0,'2026-03-26 06:28:30');
INSERT INTO discovery_runs VALUES(11,1,'ocean technology within 15 miles',unistr('You are a senior research analyst supporting a leadership advisor who is seeking a 6-8 week Entrepreneurship in Residence placement in Halifax, Nova Scotia. Your task is to find real, qualified ocean-focused organizations using web search.\u000a\u000aADVISOR BRIEF:\u000a- Geography: monterey, ca\u000a- Search Radius: 15 miles\u000a- Placement Start: 2026-06-01\u000a- Placement Duration: 6-8 weeks\u000a- Focus Areas: Ocean health, Ocean economy, Ocean technology, Ocean infrastructure, Blue economy\u000a- Leadership Problems She Solves: Stuck partnerships, Alignment issues, Truth-telling gaps, Decision-making bottlenecks, Cross-sector complexity, Founder-to-CEO transitions, Scaling culture during hypergrowth\u000a- Non-Negotiables: No single-species operations (salmon-only, lobster-only, etc.), No freshwater organizations, Must have genuine ocean/marine focus\u000a- Win-Win-Win Criteria: Value for the organization, positive ocean outcomes, community benefits\u000a\u000aABOUT THE ADVISOR (LESLIE):\u000aNearly 20 years helping tech executives create happier teams, aligned outcomes, and stronger ROI. Now transitioning to ocean conservation / blue economy leadership advisory. Specializes in: stuck partnerships, alignment issues, truth-telling gaps, strategic knots. Works best 1:1 with senior leaders or with top teams on defined missions.\u000a- Works best 1:1 with senior leaders or with top teams on defined missions\u000a- Looking for a 6-8 week Entrepreneurship in Residence placement\u000a- Offering condensed senior advisory (equivalent of a year-long engagement in 2 months)\u000a- Best fit: organizations creating win-win-wins for corporations, nature, and future generations\u000a- Includes: for-profit companies, non-profits, NGOs, public-private partnerships, social enterprises, research institutions — any organization type\u000a\u000aGEOGRAPHY CONSTRAINT:\u000a- Primary location: monterey, ca\u000a- Search radius: within 15 miles of monterey, ca\u000a- Only include organizations headquartered or with major operations within this radius\u000a\u000aSEARCH TASK:\u000aSearch for: "ocean technology within 15 miles"\u000a\u000aHARD FILTERS — Qualitative Exclusions Only:\u000a- EXCLUDE: Any organization that operates exclusively on a single marine species (salmon-only farms, lobster harvesters, tuna fisheries, whale conservation, sea turtle rescue)\u000a- EXCLUDE: Any freshwater organization (lakes, rivers, freshwater fisheries)\u000a- EXCLUDE: ExxonMobil Canada, Shell Canada, SBM Offshore (enterprise-scale oil & gas — placement impractical)\u000a- Do NOT use the broad keyword ''offshore'' — use ''offshore wind'' only\u000a- Budget and headcount are NOT exclusion criteria — return all qualifying organizations regardless of size\u000a\u000aKEYWORD SEARCH STRATEGY — Two-Axis Search:\u000aSearch for organizations using ANY of these sector terms:\u000a\u000aPRIMARY (Sector Synonyms): ocean, marine, maritime, blue economy, oceanographic, offshore wind, subsea, coastal\u000a\u000aECONOMIC FRAMING: blue finance, ocean economy, marine commerce, ocean investment, investing in ocean, ocean-focused fund, marine investment, ocean venture, sustainable seafood investment, coastal economy investment, ocean-focused accelerator\u000a\u000aINFRASTRUCTURE & OPERATIONS: marine infrastructure, offshore wind operations, offshore wind development, shipbuilding, naval architecture, port authority, marine logistics, harbour management, underwater systems, marine engineering\u000a\u000aSCIENCE & DEEP TECHNOLOGY: ocean technology, oceanography, marine science, AUV, ROV, underwater acoustics, hydrography, bathymetry, ocean intelligence, marine sensing, seabed mapping, ocean data\u000a\u000aCONSERVATION & SUSTAINABILITY: ocean stewardship, marine conservation, ocean health, blue carbon, coastal resilience, marine protected areas, ocean sustainability, ocean governance\u000a\u000aGOVERNANCE & POLICY: marine spatial planning, ocean policy, coastal management, fisheries management (broad-mandate only), marine regulatory, EEZ\u000a\u000aFOOD SYSTEMS (handle with care — enforce single-species exclusion): aquaculture (multi-species only), mariculture, sustainable seafood, seafood supply chain, blue food\u000a\u000aALSO PRIORITIZE organizations showing these LEADERSHIP SIGNALS:\u000afounder-led scaling, hypergrowth, cross-sector partnership, strategic transition, joint venture, public-private partnership, multi-stakeholder, organizational alignment, board transition, scaling culture\u000a\u000aGEOGRAPHIC NOTE: Always pair economic/investment terms with Halifax, Nova Scotia, or Atlantic Canada.\u000a\u000aLEADERSHIP SIGNAL TIER INSTRUCTION:\u000aFor every organization returned, assess and report a leadership_signal_tier value:\u000a- Use ''confirmed'' if you found specific, dateable evidence of a leadership challenge (news article about rapid hiring, founder transition announcement, partnership press release, job posting for Chief People Officer, board change filing)\u000a- Use ''inferred'' if the org''s profile strongly implies a current leadership challenge without direct evidence (recent significant funding round, newly commercialized product, recently expanded government mandate, recent merger/restructure)\u000a- Use ''unknown'' if you could not find sufficient public information to assess leadership challenges\u000a\u000aCRITICAL DISTINCTION: ''unknown'' means the data does not exist to assess — it does NOT mean no leadership challenge exists. Low public profile ≠ no leadership challenge. Never conflate absence of data with absence of challenge. All three tiers are included in results; ''unknown'' is never an exclusion reason.\u000a\u000aFor ''unknown'' tier, set leadership_signal_evidence to: ''Insufficient public data to assess leadership challenges. Recommend direct outreach to verify organizational context before pursuing.''\u000a\u000aEXCLUSION RULES (reinforced):\u000a- No single-species operations: salmon-only, lobster-only, tuna-only, shrimp-only, whale conservation, sea turtle rescue\u000a- No freshwater organizations: lake research, river conservation, freshwater fisheries\u000a- No organizations outside 15 miles of monterey, ca\u000a- Do NOT confuse ''no public data found'' with ''no leadership challenges detected''\u000a\u000aHALIFAX OCEAN ECOSYSTEM REFERENCE:\u000aCross-reference these known Nova Scotia ocean sector organizations when searching. Include them if they meet criteria, and search for additional qualifying organizations beyond this list:\u000a\u000aOCEAN TECH & SCIENCE:\u000a- Kraken Robotics — subsea technology, sonar, AUVs\u000a- Kongsberg Maritime Canada — maritime sensors and systems\u000a- GeoSpectrum Technologies — underwater acoustics\u000a- Innovasea — ocean tracking and aquaculture technology\u000a- JASCO Applied Sciences — ocean acoustics, environmental monitoring\u000a- AML Oceanographic — oceanographic instruments\u000a- Ultra Electronics Maritime Systems — defence and marine electronics\u000a- General Dynamics Canada — defence and ocean systems\u000a- Lockheed Martin Canada — defence, maritime surveillance\u000a- metOcean Telematics — ocean data buoys and telemetry\u000a- Fugro GeoSurveys — seabed mapping, geophysical survey\u000a- MDA (MacDonald Dettwiler) — satellite intelligence and earth observation\u000a- DSM Nutritional Products — marine ingredients/omega-3s\u000a- Acadian Seaplants — seaweed / marine agriculture\u000a- Ocean Sonics — hydrophones and marine acoustics\u000a- MacArtney Underwater Technology — underwater connectors and systems\u000a- CarteNav Solutions — maritime surveillance software\u000a- Deep Vision Inc. — underwater imaging and inspection\u000a\u000aOCEAN INFRASTRUCTURE & ENERGY:\u000a- Irving Shipbuilding — federal shipbuilding ($29.3B contract), Halifax\u000a- Babcock Canada — naval engineering and ship lifecycle support\u000a- FORCE (Fundy Ocean Research Centre for Energy) — tidal energy R&D\u000a- SNC-Lavalin — engineering, ocean infrastructure projects\u000a- ABCO Industries — marine fabrication\u000a\u000aDO NOT PURSUE (out of scope):\u000a- SBM Offshore — oil & gas production systems; enterprise scale\u000a- ExxonMobil Canada — offshore oil & gas major\u000a- Shell Canada — offshore energy exploration\u000a\u000aTRANSPORTATION & LOGISTICS:\u000a- Port of Halifax / Halifax Port Authority — major Atlantic port\u000a- Halterm Container Terminal — port operations\u000a- Atlantic Towing — offshore marine services\u000a- Secunda Canada — offshore marine and oil field services\u000a- Horizon Maritime Services — offshore vessel support\u000a- Oceanex — marine shipping, Atlantic Canada\u000a\u000aFISHERIES (broad ocean operations only):\u000a- High Liner Foods — global seafood processing, HQ Lunenburg NS\u000a- Clearwater Seafoods — premium shellfish, national and international scale\u000a\u000aEDUCATION & RESEARCH:\u000a- Bedford Institute of Oceanography (BIO) — federal ocean research, Dartmouth NS\u000a- Dalhousie University — Faculty of Science, ocean/marine programs\u000a- DRDC Atlantic — Defence Research & Development Canada, maritime focus\u000a- National Research Council Canada (NRC) — ocean science and engineering\u000a- COVE (Centre for Ocean Ventures & Entrepreneurship) — Halifax ocean innovation hub\u000a\u000aNETWORKS & ASSOCIATIONS:\u000a- OTCNS (Ocean Technology Council of Nova Scotia)\u000a- Ocean Tracking Network — Dalhousie, global ocean monitoring\u000a- COINAtlantic — Coastal and Ocean Information Network Atlantic\u000a\u000aOUTPUT FORMAT:\u000aReturn your results as a JSON array with this exact structure. Include both organization fields AND lead contact fields:\u000a[\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "Organization Name",\u000a    "location": "City, Province (or full address)",\u000a    "website": "https://...",\u000a    "estimated_size": 100,\u000a    "estimated_budget": "$50M",\u000a    "mission_focus": "Brief description of their mission...",\u000a    "why_fit": "Why this org is a fit for the advisor...",\u000a    "keyword_category": "sector",\u000a    "signal_strength": "high",\u000a    "leadership_signal_tier": "confirmed",\u000a    "leadership_signal_evidence": "Specific evidence found: recently announced...",\u000a    "lat": 44.6488,\u000a    "lng": -63.5752,\u000a    "contact_name": "Jane Smith",\u000a    "contact_email": "jsmith@org.com",\u000a    "contact_position": "CEO and Executive Director",\u000a    "contact_linkedin": "https://linkedin.com/in/janesmith",\u000a    "contact_bio": "15 years in ocean technology, previously led...",\u000a    "review_status": "Lead for Business",\u000a    "host_producer_notes": "Strong fit — $50M budget, ocean-wide mission, leadership transition underway"\u000a  }\u000a]\u000a\u000aFIELD NOTES:\u000a- keyword_category: one of "sector", "infra", "econ", "sci", "gov", "cons", "food" — which cluster best describes this org. Use "cons" for conservation/sustainability orgs. Use "food" for aquaculture, seafood supply chain, and blue food orgs.\u000a- signal_strength: one of "high", "strong", "supplemental", "careful" — how strong a lead for Leslie\u000a- leadership_signal_tier: one of "confirmed", "inferred", "unknown" — evidence quality for leadership challenge\u000a- leadership_signal_evidence: 1-3 sentences describing specific evidence or standard ''insufficient data'' note\u000a- lat/lng: approximate coordinates for Halifax-area mapping (decimal degrees)\u000a- review_status: one of "Lead for Business", "Lead for Review", "Pending Review", "Do NOT Contact"\u000a\u000aCOUNT AND QUALITY:\u000aReturn between 10 and 15 results. Prefer verified organizations with web-searchable evidence over speculative results. Do not return fewer than 10 results. Distribute across all three signal tiers — do not exclude unknown-tier orgs to meet a count target. Sort by estimated budget (high to low) with signal tier as tiebreaker.\u000a\u000aReturn ONLY the JSON array, no other text.'),unistr('```json\u000a[\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute (MBARI)",\u000a    "location": "7700 Sandholdt Rd, Moss Landing, CA 95039",\u000a    "website": "https://www.mbari.org/",\u000a    "estimated_size": 220,\u000a    "estimated_budget": ">$50M (primarily funded by Packard Foundation)",\u000a    "mission_focus": "Advanced research and education in ocean science and technology, developing instruments, systems, and methods for scientific research in deep waters. Focus on marine biology, geology, chemistry, and biological oceanography, AUVs, ROVs, ocean observatories.",\u000a    "why_fit": "MBARI''s focus on developing new oceanographic research tools and techniques (AUVs, ROVs) and its interdisciplinary approach aligns well with Leslie''s tech background and interest in ocean technology. Their mission to advance ocean science and technology creates significant opportunities for strategic partnerships and scaling complex projects, areas where Leslie''s expertise in ''stuck partnerships'' and ''cross-sector complexity'' would be highly valuable.",\u000a    "keyword_category": "sci",\u000a    "signal_strength": "high",\u000a    "leadership_signal_tier": "inferred",\u000a    "leadership_signal_evidence": "MBARI is a world center for advanced research, continually developing new tools and methods (AUVs, ROVs, MARS observatory). This continuous innovation and technological advancement imply ongoing strategic decisions, resource allocation challenges, and potential for scaling new technologies into broader applications, suggesting inherent leadership challenges in managing hypergrowth and cross-sector complexity.",\u000a    "lat": 36.8064,\u000a    "lng": -121.7850,\u000a    "contact_name": "Christopher Scholin",\u000a    "contact_email": "N/A (recommend general info@mbari.org or outreach through website)",\u000a    "contact_position": "President and Chief Executive Officer",\u000a    "contact_linkedin": "N/A",\u000a    "contact_bio": "N/A",\u000a    "review_status": "Lead for Business",\u000a    "host_producer_notes": "Strong alignment with tech-to-ocean transition. Large, well-funded institution with complex R&D operations, ideal for Leslie''s strategic advisory expertise."\u000a  },\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "Monterey Bay Aquarium",\u000a    "location": "886 Cannery Row, Monterey, CA 93940",\u000a    "website": "https://www.montereybayaquarium.org/",\u000a    "estimated_size": 500,\u000a    "estimated_budget": ">$50M (internationally renowned, significant operations)",\u000a    "mission_focus": "Inspiring conservation of the ocean through exhibits, education, research, and policy advocacy. Key programs include kelp forest restoration, ocean conservation, and the Seafood Watch program promoting sustainable seafood.",\u000a    "why_fit": "The Aquarium''s recent CEO transition presents a confirmed leadership challenge for Leslie. Their broad mission encompassing conservation, education, and policy advocacy, along with their ''Seafood Watch'' program, offers diverse areas for Leslie to apply her skills in strategic transitions, organizational alignment, and building cross-sector partnerships for positive ocean outcomes and community benefits.",\u000a    "keyword_category": "cons",\u000a    "signal_strength": "high",\u000a    "leadership_signal_tier": "confirmed",\u000a    "leadership_signal_evidence": "The Monterey Bay Aquarium named Jenny Gray as its new CEO on February 26, 2026, replacing founding director Julie Packard after four decades. This represents a significant ''founder-to-CEO transition'' and strategic shift for the organization. The Aquarium also has an ''Equity Roadmap'' with six priorities for staff development and inclusive leadership (2024–2028), indicating ongoing organizational alignment and culture scaling efforts.",\u000a    "lat": 36.6186,\u000a    "lng": -121.9014,\u000a    "contact_name": "Jenny Gray",\u000a    "contact_email": "N/A (recommend general info@mbayaq.org or outreach through website)",\u000a    "contact_position": "CEO",\u000a    "contact_linkedin": "N/A",\u000a    "contact_bio": "Known as one of the most influential zoo leaders in the world and a passionate champion for conservation.",\u000a    "review_status": "Lead for Business",\u000a    "host_producer_notes": "Ideal opportunity with a clear leadership transition, global reach, and a strong mission. Leslie''s experience in founder-to-CEO transitions is a direct match."\u000a  },\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "Hopkins Marine Station of Stanford University",\u000a    "location": "120 Oceanview Blvd, Pacific Grove, CA 93950",\u000a    "website": "https://hopkins.stanford.edu/",\u000a    "estimated_size": 50,\u000a    "estimated_budget": "N/A (part of Stanford University, likely significant research funding)",\u000a    "mission_focus": "A leading marine science research and education center focusing on fundamental biology of marine plants and animals, evolution, species interaction, environmental DNA, conservation of fisheries, and biomechanics of foraging whales.",\u000a    "why_fit": "Hopkins Marine Station''s integration into the new Stanford Doerr School of Sustainability and the formation of a new Oceans Department indicate significant strategic transitions and organizational alignment challenges. Their explicit concerns about sea level rise planning and maintaining aging infrastructure also present ''decision-making bottlenecks'' and ''cross-sector complexity'' for which Leslie''s advisory would be highly relevant.",\u000a    "keyword_category": "sci",\u000a    "signal_strength": "strong",\u000a    "leadership_signal_tier": "confirmed",\u000a    "leadership_signal_evidence": "As of September 1, 2022, Hopkins Marine Station became part of the new Stanford Doerr School of Sustainability, joining an inaugural Oceans Department. This signifies a major ''strategic transition'' and ''organizational alignment'' effort. The leadership team is also ''faced with the competing priorities of planning for sea level rise through retreat, new coastal armoring such as seawalls and maintaining existing yet aging infrastructure''.",\u000a    "lat": 36.6212,\u000a    "lng": -121.9214,\u000a    "contact_name": "Fiorenza Micheli",\u000a    "contact_email": "N/A (recommend general info@hopkins.stanford.edu)",\u000a    "contact_position": "Co-director of the Station and Stanford Center for Ocean Solutions, Chair of Oceans Department",\u000a    "contact_linkedin": "N/A",\u000a    "contact_bio": "David and Lucile Packard Professor of Marine Science, whose marine ecology lab is located at the research station.",\u000a    "review_status": "Lead for Business",\u000a    "host_producer_notes": "Academic setting but with clear, dateable leadership challenges and a strong focus on impactful marine science and sustainability. Excellent fit for Leslie''s strategic and alignment expertise."\u000a  },\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "Moss Landing Marine Laboratories (MLML)",\u000a    "location": "8272 Moss Landing Rd, Moss Landing, CA 95039",\u000a    "website": "https://www.mlml.calstate.edu/",\u000a    "estimated_size": 100,\u000a    "estimated_budget": "N/A (consortium of CSU campuses, significant public funding)",\u000a    "mission_focus": "Providing hands-on, field-oriented marine science education and research through a consortium of California State Universities. Focus areas include oceanography, marine biology, and applied topics relevant to state, federal, and international governance.",\u000a    "why_fit": "As a consortium, MLML likely faces ''cross-sector complexity'' and ''alignment issues'' among its constituent universities, as well as ''decision-making bottlenecks'' related to shared resources and strategic direction. Their emphasis on applied research and training the next generation of scientists suggests a need for strong leadership in translating research into real-world solutions and scaling educational programs.",\u000a    "keyword_category": "sci",\u000a    "signal_strength": "strong",\u000a    "leadership_signal_tier": "inferred",\u000a    "leadership_signal_evidence": "MLML is a consortium of seven California State Universities, offering a thesis-based master''s degree. The nature of a consortium implies ongoing ''alignment issues'' and ''cross-sector complexity'' in coordinating research, education, and funding across multiple academic institutions. The expansion of the NOAA-relevant STEM disciplines and social sciences via CCME-II program suggests ''scaling culture'' during growth.",\u000a    "lat": 36.8049,\u000a    "lng": -121.7890,\u000a    "contact_name": "N/A",\u000a    "contact_email": "N/A (recommend general info@mlml.calstate.edu or outreach through website)",\u000a    "contact_position": "Director (placeholder)",\u000a    "contact_linkedin": "N/A",\u000a    "contact_bio": "N/A",\u000a    "review_status": "Lead for Review",\u000a    "host_producer_notes": "Multi-university consortium could be a good fit for Leslie''s cross-sector complexity and alignment skills, but specific leadership challenges would need to be confirmed."\u000a  },\u000a  {\u000a    "name": "California Marine Sanctuary Foundation",\u000a    "location": "99 Pacific Street, Suite 155A, Monterey, CA 93940",\u000a    "website": "https://californiamsf.org/",\u000a    "estimated_size": 10,\u000a    "estimated_budget": "$71.1M (recent grant funding)",\u000a    "mission_focus": "Addressing climate risks in California''s Monterey Bay region, specifically flooding and wildfires, through integrated adaptation strategies, including nature-based solutions and workforce development.",\u000a    "why_fit": "With a significant recent grant ($71.1M) for the ''Regional Adaptation for Climate Resilience of Monterey Bay Coastal Communities,'' this organization is likely experiencing ''hypergrowth'' and ''scaling culture'' challenges. Their focus on multi-benefit adaptation solutions and comprehensive work